2. favete linguis: literally ‘⁵ be favourable with your tongues,'' an expression used by Roman priests when commencing a sacrifice. It was equivalent to a request that none of the bystanders should utter any word of evil omen, and so mar the ceremony, whence it means ‘⁶ be silent.'' Horace is speaking as if he were the priest of the Muses, and as if his Odes were religious. The profanum volyus means all who cannot appreciate this poetry, because such persons

are “ outside the sanctuary ’' (pro, fanum) of the Muses.
